1. What is the Two Pointer Technique?

Two Pointer is a problem-solving technique where two indices (pointers) traverse a data structure (usually an array or string) together in a coordinated way to reduce time complexity.


ðŸ‘‰ Instead of checking all pairs (O(nÂ²)), we use logic to move pointers smartly and solve in O(n).

ðŸ”¹ 2. Uses of Two Pointer Technique

Two pointers are commonly used when:

Array or string is sorted

Need to find pairs / subarrays

Comparing elements from both ends

Removing duplicates in-place

Reversing or partitioning data

Real interview use cases:

Pair sum problems

Palindrome checking

Sliding window optimization

Merging sorted arrays

Partitioning arrays

ðŸ”¹ 3. Working (How Two Pointers Work)

General flow:

Initialize two pointers

left = 0

right = n - 1

Evaluate condition using arr[left] and arr[right]

Move:

left++ OR

right--

Continue until left < right

ðŸ’¡ Key idea:
Each move eliminates unnecessary comparisons

ðŸ”¹ 4. Typical Approach (Template)
Generic Two Pointer Template
int left = 0, right = arr.length - 1;

while (left < right) {
    if (condition satisfied) {
        // do work
        left++;
        right--;
    } else if (need smaller value) {
        left++;
    } else {
        right--;
    }
}

Why this works?

Each pointer moves at most N times

Total operations â‰ˆ O(n)

